    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1961-03-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1961-03-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="55"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d55">
                <head>55. Memorandum From the Presidentʼs Special Assistant (<persName
                        corresp="#p_SAMJ1" type="from">Schlesinger</persName>) to President
                        <persName corresp="#p_KJF2" type="to">Kennedy</persName>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d55fn0">Source: <persName corresp="#p_KJF2"
                            >Kennedy</persName> Library, Presidentʼs Office Files, Countries Series,
                        Cuba, Security, 1961. Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1961-03-10">March 10, 1961</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Cuba</item>
                </list>
                <p>I very much hope that your Saturday<note n="1" xml:id="d55fn1">March 11. See <ref
                            target="#d59">Document 59</ref>.</note> meeting will consider the
                    problem of launching a comprehensive campaign to acquaint the hemisphere with
                    the facts of the <persName corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName> situation. Such a
                    campaign would seem an indispensable preliminary to any hard decisions on
                    Cuba.</p>
                <p>The recent willingness of liberal leaders, like Betancourt of Venezue-la and Haya
                    de la Torre of Peru, to condemn the <persName corresp="#p_CRF1"
                        >Castro</persName> regime suggests that the time is ripe for a propaganda
                    counter-offensive. A number of Latin Americans urged on me the importance of
                    getting people to understand what has really happened in Cuba.</p>
                <p>The campaign should consider the possibility of utilizing a variety of media
                    through the hemisphere to make some sober points about the <persName
                        corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName> regime—its Communist character, its
                    provision of facilities to the <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>, its
                    refusal to cooperate with the OAS, its intervention in the internal affairs of
                    other republics, etc.</p>
                <p>You might want to put together a group to look into this. I would suggest
                        <persName corresp="#p_BAA2">Berle</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_MER1"
                        >Murrow</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_MTC1">Mann</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_GRN2">Goodwin</persName> and myself.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SAMJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Arthur Schlesinger, Jr.</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
